english:
  title: The Third Chamber
  author: Choi Yu-cheong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly reflect that reverence for ancestors precedes all virtues, and we honor them through seasonal offerings, maintaining the proper order of the ancestral tablets. Filial piety finds no greater expression than in glorifying one's parents, and we strengthen their renown by repaying the abundance of their merit. Following the eternal rites, we conduct the highest ceremonies with utmost respect.

    I reverently contemplate King Deok-jong, the Wise and Virtuous: he embodied sacred wisdom and inherited the brilliance of his line. His martial glory greatly continued his honored father's legacy, and his benevolent governance surpassed even the wisdom of the Zhou kings. In all his plans and deeds, he understood the harmony of ten thousand matters, and through careful deliberation, he brought peace to all people under heaven. Thus do we sing of his nine accomplishments, and ten thousand generations shall forever benefit from his reign.

    Queen Gyeong-seong, of the Kim clan, possessed a gentle and virtuous nature, cultivating herself through frugality and restraint. Her ambition lay in elevating the worthy, thereby establishing the foundation of human relations, and her compassion extended to all people, securing the basis of royal transformation. She became the model of the inner palace, her brilliance shining like the crimson writing brush.

    I, your humble servant, accepted this great mandate to bring peace to my people, humbly receiving the wise counsel from above. I constantly held close the difficulty of preserving the sacred vessels, and maintained the grave concern of one standing at the precipice of an abyss. When treacherous factions betrayed the realm and spread false doctrines to deceive the people, calamity arose within the palace walls, reducing the royal residence to ashes. When rebel forces emerged from the western lands, weapons clashed and chaos spread. Yet by the grace of the divine spirit of our ancestors in heaven, we were able to quell the turmoil and restore order. Thus have we recovered what King Xuan of Zhou restored in his ancestral shrine, fulfilling what the Tang Emperor Xian-zong accomplished when he pacified Huai-xi. Heaven and humanity have harmonized, and both inner court and outer realm rejoice together. The abundance we pass to our descendants continues to receive endless blessing, and in our gratitude we recognize the limitlessness of such grace.

    On this auspicious day, we solemnly perform the ritual of libation and offering, and respectfully present the posthumous titles. With utmost reverence, we offer these tokens of devotion and present this proclamation, granting the title of Great King to [his name], and the title of Queen to [her name]. May the divine spirits, in their infinite wisdom, regard with compassion the sincerity of our hearts, and may they bring prosperity to our descendants for ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Third Chamber' (第三室) likely refers to the third generation in the ancestral temple or a specific ritual space dedicated to honoring ancestors in the royal genealogy.
    - References to 'Zhou King' and 'King Xuan of Zhou' invoke classical Chinese precedent for virtuous governance.
    - The 'crimson writing brush' (彤管) is a traditional symbol of the virtue of queens and noble women in East Asian literature.
    - The mention of 'Huai-xi' (淮西) refers to a famous historical rebellion that Tang Emperor Xian-zong successfully suppressed, serving as a parallel to the contemporary crisis being commemorated.
